<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by Squid69 on 09-06-2000 08:28 PM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I'm a major java proponent as well.

If it's a command line interface like DOS debug, doing the client in java is a no-brainer.  About 30 minutes of coding.

The server side is also a no brainer except for ONE problem, and that is actually changing the memory.  It could be possible to use JNI to call out to a DLL or WinHack though i don't have much experience using JNI so I wouldn't be much help there.  Actually writing the client and server are easy though.

Tzung, I don't have the URL to the winhack site, sorry man.  I'll poke around and see if I can find it.

A quick question to ask yourself though is: what do you hope to accomplish by writing this Application?  Not to flame or slam you, I too thought it would be neat.  But, after further examination, most of the actual "holes" in the EQ client have been fixed by moving them onto th server.  Even trading no-drop items is of questionable value and can very easily be tracked.  Anyway, it's just my two cents.  In the end, I just scrapped the idea because I found a bunch of other things to play around with.

One idea that I thought would be great is to analyze the packets going to and from the EQ servers and be able to write your own robot.  One that would log into your account and play while you sleep to get you levels.  My interest in this comes from something I wrote for Xenix (like Unix) as a kid.  It was basically a MUD.  The world server was a process and every mob and NPC in the world was a process as well completely detached from the world.  The great thing about this model is that all mobs, NPCs, and PCs are treated equally by the world.  I would code the NPCs using a scripting language then launch each NPC as a process that would in turn, connect to the world server.  I think it might be possible to do this in EQ by understanding how to manipulate the packets going to and coming from the server.  Just a thought  <IMG SRC="http://www.hackersquest.gomp.ch/ubb/smile.gif">.

Good luck to ya!
Squid

[This message has been edited by Squid69 (edited 09-06-2000).]</TEXTAREA>
